cs.SI, cs.IT, cs.LG, cs.NA, cs.DS 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper deals with graph filtering, which is a key technique in processing signals supported on the vertices of a graph. This is a common problem in social and information networks, where signals can represent user behavior, network traffic, etc. 
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper analyzes the statistical behavior of graph filters when operating on random time-varying graph signals. This involves studying the impact of stochasticity on the filter output, which is a problem that falls under the purview of information theory. 
3. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper proposes two novel ways of exploiting randomness to improve noise cancellation and reduce computational complexity. These are common problems in machine learning, where large datasets and complex models can lead to computational bottlenecks. 
4. cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) - The paper presents numerical results to demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed methods. This involves solving optimization problems and evaluating the performance of the filters, which are tasks that fall under the purview of numerical analysis. 
5. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper proposes methods to reduce the computational complexity of graph filtering. This involves designing efficient algorithms and data structures to process large graphs, which is a common problem in data structures and algorithms.
